== The Conversation ==

http://theconversation.com/discus-farce-prompts-points-pow-wow-at-paralympics-9284

Not sure if this is a reliable source; it seems to use scholars, ''but'' it still has traits of a user-generated [[content farm]]. Could we go over this just to be sure? On the page itself, it was [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=2012_Summer_Paralympics&diff=605564590&oldid=605519425 used in conjunction with more definitively reliable sources]. <span style="border:1px solid #f57900;padding:1px;"><font style="color:#8f5902">[[User:ViperSnake151|ViperSnake151]]</font> [[User_talk:ViperSnake151|<font style="color:#fff;background:#fcaf3e;">&nbsp;Talk&nbsp;</font>]] </span> 05:39, 24 April 2014 (UTC)

:It's a RS: the author is a university professor writing within his field of expertise. Most authors published by The Conversation are academic experts or experienced journalists, and all content is professionally edited. Some contributors are students and other non-experts, but their submissions are also professionally edited before being accepted or published and can be assumed to be accurate (though probably not great sources for Wikipedia articles). Calling the site a "user-generated content farm" is completely wrong. [[User:Nick-D|Nick-D]] ([[User talk:Nick-D|talk]]) 01:16, 25 April 2014 (UTC)

:With contributors like [[Ken_Henry_(public_servant)|Ken Henry]] and [[Michelle Grattan]], it's a reliable source. And well worth reading. --[[User:Skyring|Pete]] ([[User talk:Skyring|talk]]) 22:32, 28 April 2014 (UTC)

== [[Richard Sears (pilgrim)]] ==
Could someone please check this edit:
[http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Richard_Sears_%28pilgrim%29&diff=484385249&oldid=452656472].
It inserted a text starting with "The above entry is entirely erroneous and was categorically disproven by Samuel Pearce May in his definitive 1890 genealogical work," into the article. It was added in 2012 by an IP user. [[User:Ninety Mile Beach|Ninety Mile Beach]] ([[User talk:Ninety Mile Beach|talk]]) 21:26, 28 April 2014 (UTC)

:The inserted text is pretty much correct. The current standard source to consult on [[Great Migration]] immigrants is Anderson, Robert Charles, George F. Sanborn, Jr., Melinde Lutz Sanborn, ''The Great Migration: Immigrants to New England 1634-1635'', New England Historic Genealogical Society, Boston, 2001. The entry for Richard Sears confirms that the English pedigree for Richard Sears set forth in the middle of the 19th century was disproven by Samuel Pearce May in 1886, and that he published an account of the family in 1890.  The ''Great Migration'' entry further states that his origin is unknown, and that his wife was Dorothy Jones, daughter of George and Agnes Jones of Dinder, Somerset.  My only quibble would be that we can't really call an 1890 genealogical treatise definitive; for example, Donald Lines Jacobus published a brief account of the family of Richard Sears in 1948.  I will try to update the article so it's in accord with current knowledge. - <span style="font-family: cursive">[[User:Nunh-huh|Nunh-huh]]</span> 02:56, 29 April 2014 (UTC)

:I've now edited the article to standard form (from its previous point/counterpoint arrangement). Of interest: the earliest versions of this article got it right, and somewhere in the interim the bogus claims of ancestry were introduced.  - <span style="font-family: cursive">[[User:Nunh-huh|Nunh-huh]]</span> 04:18, 29 April 2014 (UTC)

