== Fansites as sources for sport stats? ==

A huge amount of statistical data has been added to the [[snooker]] articles using these two sources:

*[http://www.cuetracker.net/ CueTracker] (about [http://snookerhq.com/2014/02/11/big-interview-ron-florax-cuetracker/ the author])
*[http://snookerinfo.webs.com/ Snooker Info]

These sites are being used to sourced stuff like the number of century breaks and prize money earnings (see the infoboxes at [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] and [[Neil Robertson (snooker player)]] for the type of stuff it is sourcing. However, as convenient as these websites are they just look like fansites to me i.e. no independent editorial oversight, no serious background in sports journalism. Their use is proliferating and their use is becoming contentious. Can [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Snooker]] please have a definitive ruling on whether these sites are admissable sources? [[User:Betty Logan|Betty Logan]] ([[User talk:Betty Logan|talk]]) 14:49, 28 April 2014 (UTC)
::In most cases, fan sites are not acceptable. Many fan sites will look very slick and seem like a reliably published site, but these do not appear to have any real links to anything official and seem pretty straight forward as someone (anyone) who created a web site about their favorite subject.--[[User:Mark Miller|Maleko Mela]] ([[User talk:Mark Miller#top|talk]])  20:05, 28 April 2014 (UTC)
:::Thanks for taking a look and commenting. [[User:Betty Logan|Betty Logan]] ([[User talk:Betty Logan|talk]]) 08:56, 29 April 2014 (UTC)

== [[Fairness_and_Accuracy_in_Reporting|Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting]] (FAIR) ==

Can I use this [http://fair.org/extra-online-articles/tpp-the-largest-corporate-power-grab-youve-never-heard-of/ media watchdog organization] as a source in the [[Trans-Pacific_Partnership|"response"]] section of this page? Thanks.--[[User:The Best There Is &#39;Snikt!&#39;|The Best There Is &#39;Snikt!&#39;]] ([[User talk:The Best There Is &#39;Snikt!&#39;|talk]]) 18:37, 26 April 2014 (UTC)
:It is an editorial column and as such represents the opinion of the author, and his notability in the area might be questioned.  The "response" section is full of "list of celebrities" and such detritus which ought to be removed as weakening its value  to readers.  
::''A group of celebrities including Sean Penn, Cher, Susan Sarandon, Jennifer Hudson, Gwyneth Paltrow, Charlize Theron, Woody Harrelson, Cameron Diaz, Alicia Silverstone, Emily Deschanel, Olivia Munn, Ellen DeGeneres, Oliver Stone, Jennifer Aniston, and William Shatner have called on the United States to not sign the TPP until Japan bans the slaughter of dolphins in Taiji as documented in the Academy Award-winning documentary The Cove.[87][88][89][90] The petition, which was conceived by Sea Shepherd Cove Guardian Simone Reyes, was also signed by Jesse Jackson, Sea Shepherd founder Paul Watson, and People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals president Ingrid Newkirk.[89][91] ''
:is of nil value. [[User:Collect|Collect]] ([[User talk:Collect|talk]]) 12:42, 27 April 2014 (UTC)
:I don't see how they're reliable for information on this topic.  As it stands, they're barely good for what they do outside of their own attributed opinion. [[User:Thargor Orlando|Thargor Orlando]] ([[User talk:Thargor Orlando|talk]]) 13:08, 27 April 2014 (UTC)

:Instead of choosing a source then arguing whether it meets rs, one should choose the most relevant, high quality sources and reflect what they say.  When writing about a free trade agreement, a media watchdog is not an obvious source.  [[User:The Four Deuces|TFD]] ([[User talk:The Four Deuces|talk]]) 19:06, 27 April 2014 (UTC)

